He’ll never bar me from watching or reading things either, like, he’ll often say “proceed with extreme caution” or “I don’t think you’ll enjoy this one”
Like, there are things that’ll challenge me, and then there are things that’ll actively send me into an anxiety attack, and having someone act as a scout is so so good

When I tell people that sometimes, my partner vets media before I experience it, I’m worried they think I’m saying “my boyfriend doesn’t let me watch/read certain things”

And what I mean is “my boyfriend knows my specific triggers really well and that’s a really good resource”
You know I could probably help stimulate the economy as a consumer if I didn’t have to pay for my ADHD meds and antidepressants

I think I struggle with this because even though I’m bisexual, I’m non-binary, I still often don’t feel like I’m queer ENOUGH for the community. At the same time, I’m TOO queer to exist in cishet spaces.

Being bi is being in this weird middle ground, you can’t win. (7/7)

I see it online when an author is told by a publishing house that their story wasnt accurately depicting LGBTQIA+, when the author themself was in the community.

I saw it personally a few years ago when a lesbian ‘friend’ acted like I betrayed everyone by dating a man (6/7)

So that’s the cishet side.

But biphobia, heartbreakingly, shows up A LOT in the LGBTQIA+ side. Honestly, I see that show up more overtly 😬

It’s like there’s this idea that if you’re bi, you’re not queer enough. You’re not part of the community enough. (5/7)

Like surely I’m a wolf in sheep’s clothing, completely fooling him and trapping him in a relationship of lies.

I mean, I also can’t help but wonder why his opinion is the first thing on their mind when discussing my identity? He doesn’t govern that? I do?? (4/7)

I’ve had multiple people (family, too) with this mindset tell me outright that being bisexual means I’ll cheat on my partner.
Being in a cishet-passing relationship, I’ve gotten: “...oh, is HE aware of this? How does HE feel about this??”

They’re completely scandalized. (3/7)

Poetic, that the prefix “bi” means two, because when it comes to biphobia I definitely feel it on two fronts.

First, from the cisheteronormative side— you get the classic ‘that’s a sin’ nonsense, but then you’re also told you’re indecisive, immature, a cheater (2/7)

CW: Biphobia

So I’m in a cishet-passing relationship. That comes with a lot of privilege and I’m never gonna deny that, though at the same time I feel like that privilege has caused me to downplay/invalidate some of my own experiences, which is crappy (1/7)

As writers, it’s good to push yourself (like what @MTBlack2567 mentioned), I think if you’re avoiding writing entire types of scenes, you might not always push yourself
